1
00:00:00,160 --> 00:00:06,560
Look at this chart. Every textbook says this 
break of structure is a buy signal. So why  

2
00:00:06,560 --> 00:00:12,560
did price reverse and wipe out every single 
buyer a few bars later? It's because you've  

3
00:00:12,560 --> 00:00:17,440
been taught to look at a one-dimensional 
model. The market structure you learned  

4
00:00:17,440 --> 00:00:23,760
is a lie. Or at least it's only one-third 
of the truth. Let's fix this right now.

5
00:00:23,760 --> 00:00:29,360
My market structure analysis is based 
on three pillars: technical analysis,  

6
00:00:29,360 --> 00:00:37,440
real-time price action reading, and supply-demand 
imbalances. The synergy between them is powerful.

7
00:00:37,440 --> 00:00:43,040
Market structure begins with trends. You 
have an uptrend when price forms higher  

8
00:00:43,040 --> 00:00:50,640
highs and higher lows. You have a downtrend 
when it prints lower lows and lower highs.  

9
00:00:50,640 --> 00:00:57,280
An uptrend in day trading might last for a 
few hours before reversing or stalling. A  

10
00:00:57,280 --> 00:01:03,520
small series of bullish candles that surpass 
a previous swing high is often labeled as a  

11
00:01:03,520 --> 00:01:09,680
break of structure on the upside, affirming 
the bullish scenario. On the other hand,  

12
00:01:09,680 --> 00:01:16,640
if price consistently fails to make new highs 
and eventually breaks under a last critical low,  

13
00:01:16,640 --> 00:01:23,920
you conclude that sellers have taken control. 
That is the essence of a structural downtrend.

14
00:01:23,920 --> 00:01:29,520
In an uptrend, buyers must be pushing 
the market beyond each prior pivot to  

15
00:01:29,520 --> 00:01:36,000
maintain upward structure. But structure 
can shift quickly on intraday charts. A  

16
00:01:36,000 --> 00:01:40,480
single wave of strong selling 
might test your assumptions.

17
00:01:40,480 --> 00:01:47,040
Two vital concepts in advanced chart reading 
are break of structure and change of character.  

18
00:01:47,040 --> 00:01:52,080
A break of structure often occurs when the 
market pushes through a prior swing point  

19
00:01:52,080 --> 00:01:57,760
that was aligned with the existing trend. 
In a bullish scenario, if the price flips  

20
00:01:57,760 --> 00:02:04,480
above a prior high and closes convincingly up 
there, the structure is broken to the upside,  

21
00:02:04,480 --> 00:02:10,240
strengthening the existing uptrend. You might 
see these breaks on a 5-minute chart multiple  

22
00:02:10,240 --> 00:02:16,560
times in a bullish day. Each time they 
confirm that buyers remain in control.

23
00:02:16,560 --> 00:02:21,360
A change of character is more telling 
because it signals a potential shift in  

24
00:02:21,360 --> 00:02:28,240
balance from buyers to sellers or vice 
versa. In an uptrend, the hallmark of  

25
00:02:28,240 --> 00:02:34,720
a change of character is a failure to form a 
new higher high followed by a decisive break  

26
00:02:34,720 --> 00:02:41,600
of a key higher low. This suggests that the 
once dominant buyers are losing their grip.  

27
00:02:41,600 --> 00:02:48,000
If a price dips below a major low, it 
may be flipping from bullish to bearish.

28
00:02:48,000 --> 00:02:55,520
Markets do not always trend. Sometimes they stall 
or move sideways in a tight range. This is often  

29
00:02:55,520 --> 00:03:02,960
called consolidation or a sideways market. 
You might see a zone where for hours price  

30
00:03:02,960 --> 00:03:10,160
bounces between a support and a resistance 
with no real net progress for either side.  

31
00:03:10,160 --> 00:03:17,040
Consolidation can come before a breakout that 
resumes the prior trend or sparks a reversal.  

32
00:03:17,040 --> 00:03:22,880
It can also happen in the middle of the day when 
volume drops or the market waits for a scheduled  

33
00:03:22,880 --> 00:03:31,200
event. For day traders, reading consolidation is 
crucial, especially if you seek momentum moves.

34
00:03:31,200 --> 00:03:37,760
Price action is the raw record of trades hitting 
the market. Some see it as candlesticks with wicks  

35
00:03:37,760 --> 00:03:44,800
and real bodies. Others see it in terms of tick 
bars or footprint candles. However you visualize  

36
00:03:44,800 --> 00:03:51,360
it, price action is the best measuring instrument 
of immediate buying or selling pressure.

37
00:03:51,360 --> 00:03:58,480
Many advanced techniques revolve around watching 
how price reacts near key supply or demand zones.  

38
00:03:58,480 --> 00:04:04,960
If the price snaps up quickly off a demand region, 
you know there is healthy buying interest. If  

39
00:04:04,960 --> 00:04:11,760
it struggles to push beyond the supply zone on 
repeated attempts, that suggests strong sellers.  

40
00:04:11,760 --> 00:04:18,720
Price action is about letting the chart speak, 
not overshadowing it with lagging indicators.

41
00:04:18,720 --> 00:04:24,240
Identification of advanced price patterns 
can refine your skill. For instance, you  

42
00:04:24,240 --> 00:04:31,200
might see a short-term wedge forming in a broader 
uptrend. The wedge might break to the downside,  

43
00:04:31,200 --> 00:04:38,400
generating a quick drop that retests a prior 
demand area. Another scenario is a fake breakout  

44
00:04:38,400 --> 00:04:46,000
pattern where price runs above a known high, but 
then immediately closes below it. These patterns  

45
00:04:46,000 --> 00:04:52,320
can be powerful signals for turning points. They 
are not guaranteed, but they do highlight areas  

46
00:04:52,320 --> 00:04:59,680
where a surge of late buyers or sellers got 
trapped, often fueling the upcoming reversal.

47
00:04:59,680 --> 00:05:06,160
Advanced price patterns revolve around tracking 
expansions or impulses, and how they fade into  

48
00:05:06,160 --> 00:05:13,440
pullbacks or complex corrections. A classic 
example is a strong impulse wave up followed  

49
00:05:13,440 --> 00:05:20,240
by a three-wave correction, then another impulse 
wave up. If you confirm that each wave is printing  

50
00:05:20,240 --> 00:05:27,360
new breaks of structure on lower time frames, 
you stay confident in the overall direction.

51
00:05:27,360 --> 00:05:35,280
Another intriguing idea is to watch for pockets 
of liquidity above old highs or below old lows.  

52
00:05:35,280 --> 00:05:42,880
Price might sweep these levels for liquidity, then 
reverse swiftly. Such patterns occur regularly  

53
00:05:42,880 --> 00:05:49,520
intraday, especially if there are stops placed 
behind those pivot points. One approach is to  

54
00:05:49,520 --> 00:05:56,560
wait for a break of structure in the direction of 
the trend, then trade the retest. Another approach  

55
00:05:56,560 --> 00:06:02,800
is to watch for a potential change of character 
near a known supply zone. If you see that  

56
00:06:02,800 --> 00:06:09,920
a change of character aligns with a cluster of 
short-term double tops, that can signal a shift.

57
00:06:09,920 --> 00:06:15,440
Supply and demand revolve around the idea 
that major imbalances cause dramatic price  

58
00:06:15,440 --> 00:06:23,360
impulses. A supply zone typically forms where 
price consolidated briefly before a big drop,  

59
00:06:23,360 --> 00:06:29,920
suggesting that large sellers are positioned 
there. A demand zone is the mirror image  

60
00:06:29,920 --> 00:06:37,120
where price consolidated prior to a rapid 
climb. If price later returns to that zone,  

61
00:06:37,120 --> 00:06:40,560
you might see the same reaction from participants.

62
00:06:40,560 --> 00:06:48,240
In an intraday context, these zones might appear 
on a 15-minute chart or even a 5-minute chart if  

63
00:06:48,240 --> 00:06:53,440
the swings were particularly strong. 
They are not indefinite. Over time,  

64
00:06:53,440 --> 00:06:59,200
the orders that created the reaction 
can get absorbed or fully executed,  

65
00:06:59,200 --> 00:07:04,720
meaning the zone might lose its potency. 
But in many cases, you will see repeated  

66
00:07:04,720 --> 00:07:11,760
bounces or rejections at these zones, making 
them prime locations for structured trades.

67
00:07:11,760 --> 00:07:16,800
Some traders like to label the zone 
with the highest close or open within  

68
00:07:16,800 --> 00:07:23,600
the consolidation. Others take the entire range 
of the basing candles. The specifics can vary,  

69
00:07:23,600 --> 00:07:29,920
but the principle is consistent. Find the 
small sideways or subtle area where price  

70
00:07:29,920 --> 00:07:35,600
paused before launching a big rally 
or decline. If a rally was abrupt,  

71
00:07:35,600 --> 00:07:42,560
that implies strong buying committed in that 
base. If a drop was abrupt, that suggests intense  

72
00:07:42,560 --> 00:07:50,240
selling. When price retests the zone, watch the 
raw price action for acceptance or rejection.

73
00:07:50,240 --> 00:07:54,240
Sometimes the retest leads to 
another strong bounce in the  

74
00:07:54,240 --> 00:07:58,560
original direction. Other times the zone fails,  

75
00:07:58,560 --> 00:08:06,480
which can itself be an actionable breakout move 
that signals the supply or demand is exhausted.

76
00:08:06,480 --> 00:08:12,160
Supply and demand zones blend seamlessly 
with the idea of break of structure and  

77
00:08:12,160 --> 00:08:18,560
change of character. If you see a downtrend 
with consecutive break of structure events and  

78
00:08:18,560 --> 00:08:25,200
now price is approaching a known supply zone, 
your bias might be to fade any bullish spikes  

79
00:08:25,200 --> 00:08:32,000
into that zone. If you suspect an uptrend is 
losing steam and you see price form a change  

80
00:08:32,000 --> 00:08:38,800
of character around a previously established 
supply zone, it can be a prime short opportunity.

81
00:08:39,520 --> 00:08:46,080
Support and resistance can be more dynamic and 
advanced than just drawing a line at a pivot. An  

82
00:08:46,080 --> 00:08:53,360
advanced trader notices if support and resistance 
lines shift intraday, forming micro channels or  

83
00:08:53,360 --> 00:09:01,200
pivot flips. For example, a strong supply zone 
can turn into support if price eventually breaks  

84
00:09:01,200 --> 00:09:07,920
above it and finds new buyers on a retest. 
This shift can be observed from the magnitude  

85
00:09:07,920 --> 00:09:13,920
and speed of the breakout. If price soared 
from that supply zone, there is a good chance  

86
00:09:13,920 --> 00:09:20,240
it might function as support on the retest, 
effectively flipping from supply to demand.

87
00:09:20,240 --> 00:09:27,040
A strong demand zone can turn into resistance 
if price eventually breaks below it and finds  

88
00:09:27,040 --> 00:09:33,280
new sellers on a retest. If price broke 
that demand zone, there is a good chance  

89
00:09:33,280 --> 00:09:39,680
it might function as resistance on the 
retest, flipping from demand to supply.

90
00:09:39,680 --> 00:09:45,920
Trend lines can be a sophisticated lens for day 
traders to see dynamic support or resistance,  

91
00:09:45,920 --> 00:09:52,480
especially when combined with supply and demand. 
Suppose you have a rising channel and inside that  

92
00:09:52,480 --> 00:10:00,160
channel is an untested demand zone from a prior 
breakout. If price returns to the demand zone,  

93
00:10:00,160 --> 00:10:05,440
right where the channel's trend line meets, 
you have a confluence of signals that might  

94
00:10:05,440 --> 00:10:11,200
yield a strong bounce. That provides a 
structured approach for trade planning.  

95
00:10:11,200 --> 00:10:17,280
If price slices through that confluence, it 
might be a strong sign of a break in structure,  

96
00:10:17,280 --> 00:10:24,160
warning you that the uptrend is concluding or 
that supply overcame that pocket of demand.

97
00:10:24,160 --> 00:10:30,080
Volume analysis will help you in certain 
contexts. For instance, you may watch how  

98
00:10:30,080 --> 00:10:36,640
volume spikes at the moment price approaches a 
known supply zone. If that spike aligns with a  

99
00:10:36,640 --> 00:10:43,680
major wick rejecting the zone, that suggests 
a wave of sell orders overcame buyers.

100
00:10:44,320 --> 00:10:50,960
A footprint chart helps us see what is happening 
inside those moves by showing the volume that  

101
00:10:50,960 --> 00:10:58,080
trades at each price level during each candle. 
That way, we do not just see a candle's high  

102
00:10:58,080 --> 00:11:05,040
or low. We also see how many orders occur on 
the buying side and the selling side at each  

103
00:11:05,040 --> 00:11:12,560
tiny step of the candle. This detailed view can 
help you understand absorption and imbalances.

104
00:11:12,560 --> 00:11:16,800
Absorption is when large traders soak up orders,  

105
00:11:16,800 --> 00:11:21,760
stopping price from moving. Imbalances 
happen when there is much stronger  

106
00:11:21,760 --> 00:11:28,000
buying or selling at a particular price 
range, driving price in a direction.

107
00:11:28,000 --> 00:11:34,800
In a footprint chart, each candle is split into 
rows for each price level. You can see how many  

108
00:11:34,800 --> 00:11:41,680
contracts were traded on the bid side (the 
sellers) and on the ask side (the buyers).  

109
00:11:41,680 --> 00:11:48,320
This can paint a vivid picture of whether buyers 
or sellers are more aggressive at certain price  

110
00:11:48,320 --> 00:11:55,360
increments. When there are large blocks of sellers 
at a certain price, you often see a big number on  

111
00:11:55,360 --> 00:12:03,200
the bid column at that price. If there is strong 
buying, you see a larger number on the ask column.

112
00:12:03,200 --> 00:12:08,880
For day traders, footprint charts can 
be a revelation. They add a whole new  

113
00:12:08,880 --> 00:12:13,840
layer to market structure. They can 
show if there is absorption at a high,  

114
00:12:13,840 --> 00:12:18,640
meaning there is a strong group of 
sell orders that keeps soaking up buys,  

115
00:12:18,640 --> 00:12:25,600
so price cannot break through that same high. 
Or perhaps we see an imbalance of eager buyers  

116
00:12:25,600 --> 00:12:32,080
stepping in at a certain low, pushing price 
upward. By looking inside the candle, you  

117
00:12:32,080 --> 00:12:39,360
discover that price is not just a line or a bar. 
It is the result of orders at each small step.

118
00:12:39,360 --> 00:12:45,040
If at a critical swing low, we see an 
extremely large cluster of buy orders  

119
00:12:45,040 --> 00:12:50,960
that appear to stop further drops, that might 
warn us that the market is forming a new higher  

120
00:12:50,960 --> 00:12:57,760
low and could push up again. Whenever price 
approaches a supply or demand zone, you can  

121
00:12:57,760 --> 00:13:04,480
look at the footprint structure to see if large 
traders are unloading or absorbing positions.

122
00:13:04,480 --> 00:13:10,800
Absorption is when the market tries to move 
further in one direction like going up but  

123
00:13:10,800 --> 00:13:18,240
meets a large opposing force like big sell orders. 
Those big sell orders soak up all the buying that  

124
00:13:18,240 --> 00:13:26,560
tries to push price higher, so price cannot really 
break up. Sometimes after that we see a reversal.

125
00:13:26,560 --> 00:13:33,760
Imbalances are when one side is heavily stronger 
than the other. You might see large numbers on the  

126
00:13:33,760 --> 00:13:41,040
buy side (the ask side) with only small numbers 
on the bid side at the same price level, or  

127
00:13:41,040 --> 00:13:48,640
vice versa. This market order flow can lead to a 
swift move in the direction of the stronger force.

128
00:13:48,640 --> 00:13:54,320
You see, markets are always about balancing 
out how many are willing to buy and how many  

129
00:13:54,320 --> 00:14:01,440
are willing to sell. When that balance is tilted 
heavily in one direction, price moves quickly.  

130
00:14:01,440 --> 00:14:07,360
On footprints, an imbalance can show up when 
you see a big difference in the volume between  

131
00:14:07,360 --> 00:14:14,720
the bid and ask at a specific price. That is 
a bullish imbalance because it suggests a lot  

132
00:14:14,720 --> 00:14:19,760
more people hit the offer. They were 
eager to buy. If that keeps happening  

133
00:14:19,760 --> 00:14:25,840
across multiple price levels in a single 
candle or a short sequence of candles,  

134
00:14:25,840 --> 00:14:32,000
you know that buyers are strongly in control. 
The price often shoots up. Conversely,  

135
00:14:32,000 --> 00:14:39,120
a big imbalance on the bid side is a heavy 
wave of sells that can drive price down.

136
00:14:39,120 --> 00:14:44,320
Now, let's connect absorption and 
imbalances to the overall structure.  

137
00:14:44,320 --> 00:14:49,680
Suppose you have an uptrend. You watch 
the footprints near each pullback. This  

138
00:14:49,680 --> 00:14:55,280
is where the market dips temporarily 
but then tries to continue up. If every  

139
00:14:55,280 --> 00:15:00,160
time the price dips you see big 
buy imbalances on the footprint,  

140
00:15:00,160 --> 00:15:06,800
that signals the path is likely to keep 
going upward. The structure remains bullish.

141
00:15:06,800 --> 00:15:12,960
Or suppose price tests a previous swing high. 
Now you see heavy absorption from sellers at  

142
00:15:12,960 --> 00:15:19,920
that high. Price tries to break but cannot hold 
above that level. The footprint reveals that the  

143
00:15:19,920 --> 00:15:26,880
market is not accepting higher prices. A normal 
chart might just show a candle that poked above  

144
00:15:26,880 --> 00:15:32,320
and came back below, but the footprint 
confirms that big sellers were standing  

145
00:15:32,320 --> 00:15:40,400
in the way. That can hint at a false breakout 
or a potential reversal if it keeps happening.

146
00:15:40,400 --> 00:15:47,760
Imagine you see a strong uptrend making higher 
highs. Suddenly, it tries to push to a new high  

147
00:15:47,760 --> 00:15:54,800
but prints less buy imbalance than before. 
Actually, you notice a spike in absorption on  

148
00:15:54,800 --> 00:16:02,160
the sell side. If the market fails to hold above 
that old high and quickly returns below, forming  

149
00:16:02,160 --> 00:16:08,640
a lower swing high, you may have an early sign of 
a structure shift. The footprint is telling you  

150
00:16:08,640 --> 00:16:15,200
that the imbalance from buyers is not as strong. 
Plus, sellers are absorbing attempts to break  

151
00:16:15,200 --> 00:16:22,720
upward. That is possibly the start of a downtrend 
if the price pushes below a previous swing low.

152
00:16:22,720 --> 00:16:28,000
So, let's recap. You will find that 
repeated strong buy imbalances lead  

153
00:16:28,000 --> 00:16:33,520
to uptrends. Repeated strong sell 
imbalances lead to downtrends,  

154
00:16:33,520 --> 00:16:39,680
and absorption near a prior top or bottom 
signals a potential turning point. The  

155
00:16:39,680 --> 00:16:46,000
advantage is that you do not have to guess. You 
see how many trades occurred at each price. So  

156
00:16:46,000 --> 00:16:52,720
if a level is truly being defended by big 
orders, it becomes obvious on the chart.

157
00:16:52,720 --> 00:16:59,280
The best day trading strategies unify structural 
and supply-demand logic with real-time price  

158
00:16:59,280 --> 00:17:05,600
action cues. You don't want to rely on a 
single pattern or a single zone. Instead,  

159
00:17:05,600 --> 00:17:12,400
try to piece together the trend context. Watch 
for a break of structure or a retest near a zone.  

160
00:17:12,400 --> 00:17:19,440
Confirm on your footprint chart that buyers or 
sellers are stepping in. Then pull the trigger.

161
00:17:19,440 --> 00:17:25,360
This market is trending down strongly 
overnight. Coming into the London session,  

162
00:17:25,360 --> 00:17:31,680
the price forms a small consolidation and 
then continues down, showing multiple breaks  

163
00:17:31,680 --> 00:17:39,760
of structure to the downside. You then identify 
a supply zone that sparked a strong move lower.  

164
00:17:39,760 --> 00:17:45,200
When price retests that zone, you watch 
your footprints. If you see high levels  

165
00:17:45,200 --> 00:17:50,880
of selling aggression at that zone, it 
might confirm the continuation short.

166
00:17:50,880 --> 00:17:56,640
While the approach is universal, your personal 
plan will depend on how frequently you like to  

167
00:17:56,640 --> 00:18:02,160
trade. Some advanced day traders prefer 
waiting for quick scalp opportunities  

168
00:18:02,160 --> 00:18:07,840
around supply-demand interactions. 
Others might hold positions longer,  

169
00:18:07,840 --> 00:18:13,520
letting the entire session's trend play 
out as multiple break of structure events  

170
00:18:13,520 --> 00:18:18,560
reaffirm that they are on the right 
side. During a day, the structure can  

171
00:18:18,560 --> 00:18:25,600
shift from expansion to consolidation, from 
bullish to bearish, so you need to adapt.

172
00:18:25,600 --> 00:18:31,840
Setting up an intraday trade around the 
market structure might go like this. First,  

173
00:18:31,840 --> 00:18:38,080
you confirm the daily bias from a slightly 
higher time frame, such as a 30-minute chart,  

174
00:18:38,080 --> 00:18:44,000
to see if there is a dominant bullish or 
bearish theme. You identify major supply  

175
00:18:44,000 --> 00:18:50,240
and demand levels from that perspective. You 
then keenly watch for how price interacts with  

176
00:18:50,240 --> 00:18:57,040
those zones on your shorter time frame, maybe 
a 5-minute one. If you see an emerging break of  

177
00:18:57,040 --> 00:19:03,680
structure aligned with your bias, you look for 
confirmation in price action. That might be a  

178
00:19:03,680 --> 00:19:10,560
strong bullish candle retesting and rejecting 
a prior pivot, or a footprint reading showing  

179
00:19:10,560 --> 00:19:18,000
buyers overwhelming sellers. You enter with the 
logic being purely structural. Then if you see a  

180
00:19:18,000 --> 00:19:25,680
sign that structure might be shifting again, like 
a minor change of character, you exit or adjust.

181
00:19:25,680 --> 00:19:31,440
From a purely technical standpoint, you can 
manage a trade by letting structure guide stops  

182
00:19:31,440 --> 00:19:38,720
and targets. For example, if you go long after a 
bullish break of structure, you can place a stop  

183
00:19:38,720 --> 00:19:45,280
below the higher low that preceded your entry. 
If the market is truly continuing its uptrend,  

184
00:19:45,280 --> 00:19:51,280
that low should not be violated. For profit 
targets, you might look at the next major  

185
00:19:51,280 --> 00:19:57,840
supply zone or the next likely area for a 
structural shift. Once price gets there,  

186
00:19:57,840 --> 00:20:04,240
you re-evaluate. If you see footprints and 
price action still supportive of your thesis,  

187
00:20:04,240 --> 00:20:10,560
you might trail the stop. If not, 
you can exit, locking in your gains.

188
00:20:10,560 --> 00:20:16,880
In your market structure analysis, one pitfall 
is to read too many signals into every micro  

189
00:20:16,880 --> 00:20:23,360
swing. You see, intraday charts can be noisy 
and you do not want to leap at the first small  

190
00:20:23,360 --> 00:20:30,400
break of structure if it is overshadowed by the 
larger trend or the possibility of a false break.  

191
00:20:30,400 --> 00:20:37,040
So, please resist the urge to jump in after 
a massive directional candle. Instead,  

192
00:20:37,040 --> 00:20:42,880
wait to see if that move aligns with a 
confirmed break of structure or a retest.

193
00:20:42,880 --> 00:20:48,160
Another pitfall is ignoring the bigger 
picture. If the market is in a dominant  

194
00:20:48,160 --> 00:20:53,840
trend that has shown no true sign of 
reversal, a small change of character  

195
00:20:53,840 --> 00:20:59,760
on a very low time frame might trick 
you into a premature position. Focusing  

196
00:20:59,760 --> 00:21:07,200
too narrowly on each wave can cause constant 
second-guessing. Instead, you want to keep a  

197
00:21:07,200 --> 00:21:14,640
layered approach that spans multiple time frames 
aligned with major supply and demand references.

198
00:21:14,640 --> 00:21:19,520
Small refinements matter for day 
traders. One approach is to watch a  

199
00:21:19,520 --> 00:21:25,920
15-minute chart for structure while using 
the 5-minute footprint to refine entries.  

200
00:21:25,920 --> 00:21:31,600
You might see the 15-minute chart break 
structure for a bullish push, then switch to  

201
00:21:31,600 --> 00:21:38,640
the 5-minute to see if footprint volumes confirm 
a surge in buyer activity at the retest zone.

202
00:21:38,640 --> 00:21:44,560
Support and resistance can morph as price 
moves. A region that was tested multiple  

203
00:21:44,560 --> 00:21:51,440
times might weaken or it might accumulate more 
orders. You can watch if each subsequent retest  

204
00:21:51,440 --> 00:21:59,200
sees smaller or bigger bounces. If bigger bounces 
occur, that suggests increased demand or supply  

205
00:21:59,200 --> 00:22:05,200
stepping in. If it starts to flatten, 
perhaps you are on the verge of a break.

206
00:22:05,200 --> 00:22:12,160
Scaling in or out can be a viable technique 
if you regularly trade intraday during strong  

207
00:22:12,160 --> 00:22:19,600
trends where you are confident of a continuation. 
Rather than entering your full size all at once,  

208
00:22:19,600 --> 00:22:25,440
you might start with a partial position at 
the initial break of structure. Then if price  

209
00:22:25,440 --> 00:22:31,120
retests that break level with footprints 
confirming a surge in your direction,  

210
00:22:31,120 --> 00:22:38,960
you add more. You can exit part of your position 
at the next pivot or supply-demand zone. If the  

211
00:22:38,960 --> 00:22:45,040
structure remains strongly with you, you hold 
the rest to see if a bigger move develops.

212
00:22:45,680 --> 00:22:51,760
Your framework should revolve around 
consistent steps and definitions. For instance,  

213
00:22:51,760 --> 00:22:57,760
how exactly do you define a break of structure 
for your time frame? Is it a full close beyond  

214
00:22:57,760 --> 00:23:05,520
the level or just a wick? How many candles do you 
wait to confirm a zone retest? You might require  

215
00:23:05,520 --> 00:23:12,560
at least two consecutive closes beyond a swing 
high to call it a bullish break, for example.  

216
00:23:12,560 --> 00:23:17,520
Or you might say a supply zone is 
only valid if price left it with a  

217
00:23:17,520 --> 00:23:24,560
strong momentum candle. By clarifying these 
definitions, you reduce impulse decisions.

218
00:23:24,560 --> 00:23:32,560
Here are some rules. First, officially define how 
you recognize an uptrend or downtrend. Second,  

219
00:23:32,560 --> 00:23:40,160
clarify break of structure triggers for bullish or 
bearish continuation. Also specify the difference  

220
00:23:40,160 --> 00:23:45,360
between potential change of character 
patterns and the confirmed reversals,  

221
00:23:45,360 --> 00:23:50,400
and try to map out supply-demand 
zones in a consistent manner.

222
00:23:50,400 --> 00:23:57,120
So here is a generalized step-by-step approach to 
day trade setups using market structure. First is  

223
00:23:57,120 --> 00:24:03,600
the pre-market prep. Mark overnight highs 
and lows. Identify any high-impact supply  

224
00:24:03,600 --> 00:24:10,000
or demand zones left on the chart from the 
previous session. Then is the trend check.  

225
00:24:10,000 --> 00:24:15,680
Check the bigger time frame, the 30-minute 
or 1-hour, to see if you have an established  

226
00:24:15,680 --> 00:24:23,840
uptrend or downtrend or if you suspect a new 
change of character. Then identify key levels,  

227
00:24:23,840 --> 00:24:29,440
evaluate potential breakout points, 
pivot lines, or supply-demand zones.  

228
00:24:29,440 --> 00:24:36,400
You then monitor price action. Observe how 
price reacts near key zones. Look for bullish  

229
00:24:36,400 --> 00:24:43,840
or bearish candlestick patterns or specific micro 
structure like retests, small head-fake moves,  

230
00:24:43,840 --> 00:24:50,480
or partial breaks. Then you use footprint 
closely. In a strong bullish scenario,  

231
00:24:50,480 --> 00:24:56,880
watch if the footprint bars confirm heavy 
ask volume at or above key inflection points.  

232
00:24:56,880 --> 00:25:04,160
In a potential top scenario, look for absorption 
clusters on the bid side, then execute.

233
00:25:04,160 --> 00:25:08,480
And if you're ready to fit this 
into a full A to Z trading system,  

234
00:25:08,480 --> 00:25:15,840
that's what our academy is for. 
